span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_lightbulb.gif" align=absmiddle>  /Loc command and how to use it</span><hr size=1> For those who still need to get a greater grasp of it...or any grasp at all <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Firstly, the 3rd number in a /loc command feedback is your position on the vertical axis. Now, I can think of a couple of rare situations, where one might need that, but we're gonna skip it entirely here, so just ignore it.<br>
<br>
The 1st number is your position on the north/south axis, north being positive<br>
<br>
The 2nd number is your position on the west/east axis, west being positive<br>
<br>
If you havn't bothered with getting your Sense Heading skill up you can still use the /loc command to see where you're heading. When running along you can do the /loc (or simply /l) command a couple of times with a few seconds in between to determine heading. If you have the room you could also make a /loc hot key.<br>
<br>
Example: first time you get -2373.65,652.03,(ignore 3rd), next you get -2289.33,651.35,(ignore 3rd). Let's see, your number on the north/south axis had it's value increased in a positive direction by roughly 85, which means you're heading north. Next, your value on the west/east axis has decreased in a negative direction by hardly 1, which means you're facing just a negligable, tiny bit east. <br>
<br>
The easiest way is to just deal with the numbers one at a time; did the first number move towards positive or negative? &lt;---is like asking, am I headed north or south? Did the second number move towards positive or negative? &lt;---am I headed west or east? And pay attention to how much the numbers change in between /loc commands to know how much you're moving along the axi.<br>
<br>
I do recommend getting Sense Heading up and running even though it's a major pain to train, especially if you choose to start from scratch and not waste any valuable skill points in it. I made it a habit to train it during downtimes and meditation times. Using /loc command in conjunction with Sense Heading makes it all the easier IMO.<br>
<br>
Example: You wanna get to a specific loc point in zone: neg2500.pos2500 and you check your position to 1270.52,1009.83,(ignore 3rd). Ok, first number: You wanna get from pos1300 (I always round of to nearest hundred when giving loc points, since it's easier to remember and in most cases your character can see several hundreds in each direction) to neg2500, that means alot south. Second number: You wanna get from pos1000 to pos2500, that's westward. <br>
<br>
All in all you wanna move 3800 southward and 1500 westward, so now you use your Sense Heading until you face southwest and just start running. Now, since you have to get a lot more south than west you can turn a few nodges to your left to get a greater south bearing than west. While running in the general direction you can do /loc command to see if one of the numbers are changing too fast or too slow in relation to the other yet again in relation to how much you wanna move on the individual axis (hope I didn't go too far there <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) to redefine your heading with a little turning.<br>
<br>
Once you get good at this you'll be able to enter a zone, start running, do a couple of /loc commands, define your course in accordance, and hit the exact point you wanted to go on the other side of zone...I have gotten lucky a few times hehe.<br>
<br>
All this writing is what it is, but to really get the hang of it, I suggest you go to a safe zone and practice the hell out of it.<br>
<br>
Hope this is useful.<br>
<br>
